{"key":"processedPost-13069163","value":{"id":13069163,"first":13068284,"last":13072774,"when":1282160515,"utime":"08/18/10 10:41 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Drasman123 said:</strong><br />RR says to let the spent coffee grounds dry out in the sun on a cookie tray or something. So I plan to do that and then add it to the coir with the boiling water when i get ready to mix up my bulk substrate. Since I work at starbucks I have plenty of access to coffee grounds hahaha.<br />Barista by day, Mycologist by night...</blockquote><br />That is not a proper method of pasteurization and will lead to a high contaminant rate.&nbsp; Mix all your ingredients, add water to bring to field capacity, and then place in jars or bags and slowly heat to 140F in a pot of water.&nbsp; Keep the center of your substrate at that temp for 60 to 90 minutes.&nbsp; Don't allow the temp of the material to exceed 160F during that time.<br />You can cut gypsum back to 5% without a loss in performance.<br />RR","title":"Re: Coir / Coffee / Vermiculite Bulk Substrate"}}